i was unnerved that ahead of 'melodrama' lorde chose to release the single 'green light,' as it struck me as a mediocre aftermarket 'florence + the machine' knockoff. I feared all the mysterious kinetic energy of 2013's 'pure heroine' was just a mere one-off. however I was extremely pleased to discover that in her sophomore album lorde not only exceeded the hype, but also has come into her own both as an artist and a global personality. The irony is not lost on me that while her contemporaries busy themselves playing to the tabloids with faux melodrama in a cynical effort to promote their paint-by-numbers summer releases , lorde chose 'melodrama' as the banner under which to unleash unto the world her newest endeavor, a nuanced and disarmingly mature grasp for truth in the overlapping topics of romance, growing up, and the thin artifice of celebrity. In just eleven concise tracks, lorde has architected for us an entirely new soundscape equal in scope but apart from her breakout success 'pure heroine.' lorde has melted down all the wintery tones and dark medieval imagery that characterized the latter and molded the materiel into an amorphous, indigo landscape of dramatic, euphoric vistas overlooking long, winding and dusky valleys; a cutting metaphor for the transition from one’s teenage years to young adulthood. All along the way lorde effortlessly weaves in masterful nods toward her musical inspirations, including fellow wunderkinds like kate bush, feist, and bon iver. Teeming with the same fizzy, enchanting, deeply-intuitive pop genius as its predecessor, ‘melodrama’ is sure to rack up points on billboard charts worldwide, but beneath all that, lorde’s latest tour de force is powered by a distinctive raw emotional honesty that as yet has not been soured by the apparatus of tabloid culture.

See that if we all raise our voices, let this page know that we are woke, that we see what's going on here and we do not stand for it, that we will work together to make a change, then we can make a difference.
